                                            Privacy Policy
                                            --------------

The police collect and process data, that is the core of our work. With that we can be vigilant and helpful. We handle all this information with integrity, with respect for everyone's privacy and with the greatest possible care. In this privacy statement we show for what purpose we collect data, how we use it and what your rights are. This privacy statement can also change. In that case, we will inform you about this on our system.

1.	Definition and Interpretation
    1.1. Unless otherwise defined herein, capitalized terms and expressions used in this policy shall have the following meaning:
        1.1.1. “Authorisation” means granting access to our employees and to employees of other organizations with investigative duties.
        1.1.2. The “Data Controller” means a person who either alone or jointly or in common with other person(s) determines the purposes for which and the manner in which any personal data are, or are to be processed.
        1.1.3. The “Data Processor”, means in relation to personal data, means any person (other than an employee of the data controller) who processes the data on behalf of the data controller.
        1.1.4. “Data Protection Laws” means EU Data Protection Laws and, to the extent applicable, the data protection or privacy laws of any other country.
        1.1.5. “Data Sharing” means making police data available to those other organizations and vice versa.
        1.1.6. “Dutch Data Protection Authority” means the national supervisory authority.
        1.1.7. “GDPR” means EU General Data Protection Regulation 2016/679
        1.1.8. “Personal Data” means any Personal Data Processed by a Contracted Processor on behalf of Company pursuant to or in connection with the Principal Agreement.
        1.1.9. “Police Policy Standards” means Police Policy Standards (Wpg).
        1.1.10. “Privacy and Data Protection” means the privacy-enhancing measures.
        1.1.11. The definition “Processing”, means in relation to information or data means obtaining, recording or holding the information or data or carrying out any operation or set of operations on the information or data, including organisation, adaptation or alteration of the information or data retrieval, consultation or use of the information or data, disclosure of the information or data by transmission, dissemination or otherwise making available, alignment, combination, blocking, erasure or destruction of the information or data.
    1.2. The terms, “Commission”, “Controller”, “Data Subject”, “Member State”, “Personal Data”, “Personal Data Breach”, “Processing” and “Supervisory Authority” shall have the same meaning as in the GDPR, and their cognate terms shall be construed accordingly.
____________________________

2.	Data Controller
    2.1. The Chief of Police is the Data Controller.
    2.2. The Data Controller:
        2.2.1. determines for what purpose and by what means, how and what data will be processed.
        2.2.2. must comply with Data Protection Laws and regulations.
____________________________

3.	Processing of Personal Data
    3.1. Processor shall:
        3.1.1. comply with all applicable Data Protection Laws in the Processing of Personal Data and the Police Policy Standards; and
        3.1.2. not Processing of Personal Data other than on the relevant documented instructions.
    3.2. The Data Controller instructs Processor to process Personal Data.
____________________________

4.	Authorisation
    4.1. We give access to employees who are authorised to view the data they need to do their job	.
    4.2. The Police Policy Standards requires logging but the General Data Protection Regulation does not require logging.
    4.3. We keep track of who performs which action at what time in a particular file.
____________________________

5.	Retention Periods
    5.1. According to the Police Policy Standards:
        5.1.1. contains fixed retention periods for personal data.
        5.1.2. makes a distinction between deletion and destruction of data. Deletion of data is not permanent while destruction is a final act where data cannot be retrieved.
    5.2. A maximum period of 5 years has been set for the storage of logging data.
____________________________

6.	Data Sharing
    6.1. Data are:
        6.1.1. made available to other parties if there is a legal basis for this. 
        6.1.2. not always be used for a purpose other than that for which it was collected.
____________________________

7.	Supervision
    7.1. Data Protection Officer (DPO) monitors the application and compliance with privacy legislation internally.
    7.2. Dutch Data Protection Authority (AP) supervises the application of privacy legislation. Anyone who has complaints about the use of Personal Data or police data by the us can contact the AP.
____________________________

8.	Privacy and Data Protection
    8.1. The Data Protection assessment is carried out to know what are the effects of the data Processing on the Data Protection of citizens.
    8.2. If there appears to be a high risk of invasion of Privacy and this risk cannot be covered, we will submit the Processing to the Dutch Data Protection Authority for advice.



